name: Thimble Canyon
description:
Introduction

The reef in the Northern Swell forms short, east-facing, wide canyons with potholes. Individually these canyons aren't headliners, but together they can make a fun desination and several can be descended in a day.

Thimble is short and has one little seemingly keeper pothole.

Getting There

Drive to TH:

Option 1: From the exit on I-70 for Highway 24, head north on County Rd 1029 (S. Four Corners Mine Rd) up Buckmaster Draw for 4.8 miles. After a curve to the east, continue north on CR 1032 (South Buckmaster Rd) for 2.4 miles to the Junction of South Buckmaster Rd, North Buckmaster Rd and Smith Camp Rd.

Option 2: From I-70, drive north on US Hwy 6/191 for 4.7 miles and exit West onto County Road 1080 (Smith Camp/North Buckmaster Rd) for 2.25 miles to the same Junction.

From the Junction, continue west another 1250ft on Smith Camp Rd and park on the south side before the old structures.

Approach

On Foot:

Walk through the old structures and walk upstream in the drainage. Take the fork that is Left Up Canyon and climb the sandstone domes north of the southern drainage on the north side. Hike to the top rappel and descend.

Descent

These three rappels have not been descended as of 14May2022, but look like a fun practice area with a keeper pothole that held water in May.

Exit

Retrace the approach back to the car.
